Then the shell renderer reads this config and places CSS grid/flex areas accordingly. If you wake up one day and want tabs on the left and sidebar on the right, it's a config change, not a rewrite. The key is **CSS custom properties + grid template areas**:

```css
/* Layout driven by properties - easily swappable */
.shell {
```

```css
  --tab-bar-area: "tabs";
  --sidebar-area: "sidebar";  
  --content-area: "content";
  --alert-area: "alerts";

  display: grid;
  grid-template-areas:
    "tabs    tabs"
    "sidebar content";
  grid-template-columns: var(--sidebar-width, 0px) 1fr;
  grid-template-rows: var(--tab-bar-height, 40px) 1fr;
}

/* Flip sidebar to right? Just change the template */
.shell[data-sidebar-position="right"] {
```

```css
  grid-template-areas:
    "tabs    tabs"
    "content sidebar";
  grid-template-columns: 1fr var(--sidebar-width, 0px);
}

/* Tabs on bottom? */
.shell[data-tabs-position="bottom"] {
  grid-template-areas:
    "sidebar content"
    "tabs    tabs";
  grid-template-rows: 1fr var(--tab-bar-height, 40px);
}
```

Any orientation change is just swapping `data-*` attributes or CSS custom properties. The components themselves don't care where they are.

